Personal Heatmaps

Ernesto Carrella

July 4, 2016

Ive been working on agents being a little smarter in how they use their experience to make decisions about the future.
Currently agents work by explore-exploit. They know their best spot and they experiment every now and then with a new one. Easy. The memory size is 1 and whenever a new best is found the previous experience is erased.

Now as a step toward better cognition we want agents to make better use of their experience. In particular wed like agents to have an opinion about areas of the map they havent been to in a bit as to how profitable or unprofitable they are based on their past memories.

We accomplish this here by nearest-neighbor regression. Agents keep track of where they have been during their life-time and how much money they made. Then when asking themselves how much money they would make at position \(x\) they simply recall the closest (in terms of time and space) experience they had about it and use it as an answer.
This is easier to show than to explain.

In the next video I show two maps. The left one shows the model run with a single boat. The right map is actually the heatmap the agent is producing (red means negative profits, white means no profit, blue means high profits). Initially the heatmap is mono-color because the agent has no observations. Every time it comes back to port it adds that trips profits to his memory: the heatmap shows the neighborhood of that trip location painted with the last trip profits. Eventually the agent learns about that the most profitable spot to fish is just next to port.

Now we can have 100 agents do the same. In the next video, motion sickness warning, I show the heatmap of 4 random agents next to the usual simulation map. Agents mostly generate the same heatmap in spite of different experiences. Moreover as the area next to port becomes depleted you can see it becoming red in the agents heatmaps: they learn that the once profitable area turned bad and they now avoid it.

Next Steps

Lets start with the good stuff: nearest neighbor regression is actually quite fast. Especially when using k-d trees the simulation doesnt run that much slower compared to our usual explore-exploit. I am sure that given time Ill be able to optimize it further.
It does look rather steep especially around areas of the sea that are explored rarely but this can be improved with making the regression about the average \(k\) closest neighbors rather than just the last one.

There are a bunch of avenues for improvement. First, a heatmap is not a decision algorithm but a tool to help decisions. Currently the agents always fish (with some noise) on the highest point of the heatmap; this however is a very exploitative strategy that might result in under-exploration.

More importantly I think the key question is what factors should go in the heatmap regression? Right now the agents regress over space (\(x,y\)) and time. However it is entirely possible that different factors might matter more. For example we might want to regress over distance from port or habitat and so on.
Ill work on this in the next demo!
